# AgentCeption ‚Äî Agent Rules

## Identity

AgentCeption ‚Äî multi-agent orchestration system for AI-powered development workflows. Tagline: "the infinite machine behind the machines."

- **Entry points:** `GET /` (Build dashboard), MCP tools (Cursor/Claude). Same engine, same pipeline.
- **Stack:** Python 3.11+, FastAPI, Jinja2, HTMX, Alpine.js, SCSS, Pydantic v2, SQLAlchemy (async), Alembic. Fully async.
- **Models:** `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6` and `anthropic/claude-opus-4.6` via OpenRouter. No others.
- **Version:** Single source of truth in `pyproject.toml`.

## Agent scope

You may: implement features, fix bugs, refactor, extend architecture, add tests, update docs.
You may NOT: introduce new frameworks/dependencies without justification, redesign architecture unless requested, weaken security, skip tests.
When uncertain: (1) preserve existing patterns, (2) prefer smaller changes over rewrites, (3) choose correct over simple, (4) document assumptions, (5) ask the user.

## Architecture (do not weaken)

- **Layers:** Routes (thin) ‚Üí Services ‚Üí Models. Never collapse.
- **Planning pipeline:** Phase 1A (LLM ‚Üí PlanSpec YAML) ‚Üí Phase 1B (human review) ‚Üí Issue creation ‚Üí Agent dispatch.
- **Org tree dispatch:** CTO ‚Üí VP ‚Üí Engineer. Each tier receives the correct label scope and cognitive-architecture context.
- **No deprecated APIs:** Remove dead code on sight. No fallbacks for old API shapes.

## GitHub interactions ‚Äî MCP first

The `user-github` MCP server (officially maintained by GitHub) is available in every Cursor session. **Always prefer MCP tools over `gh` CLI for GitHub operations.** MCP calls are typed, structured, and composable; `gh` is a last resort for operations not yet covered by the server.

| Operation | MCP tool |
|-----------|----------|
| Read an issue | `issue_read` |
| Create / edit an issue | `issue_write` |
| Add an issue comment | `add_issue_comment` |
| List issues | `list_issues` |
| Search issues / PRs | `search_issues`, `search_pull_requests` |
| Read a PR | `pull_request_read` |
| Create a PR | `create_pull_request` |
| Update / merge a PR | `update_pull_request`, `merge_pull_request` |
| Create / submit a review | `pull_request_review_write` |
| List / create branches | `list_branches`, `create_branch` |
| Get current user | `get_me` |
| Search code | `search_code` |

Only fall back to `gh` CLI when the MCP server does not cover the required operation (e.g. `gh worktree`, `gh auth`).

## Execution

- **Docker-first:** Never run Python on the host. `docker compose exec agentception <cmd>`.
- **Dev bind mounts are active.** `docker-compose.override.yml` bind-mounts `agentception/`, `tests/`, `scripts/`, and `pyproject.toml` into the container. Host file edits are **instantly visible** inside the container ‚Äî no rebuild needed for code changes. Only rebuild (`docker compose build agentception && docker compose up -d`) when you change `requirements.txt`, `Dockerfile`, or `entrypoint.sh`.
- **Verification order: mypy ‚Üí tests ‚Üí docs.** Always run mypy first. Fix type errors before running tests so you only need one test pass.
- **Mypy:** `docker compose exec agentception mypy agentception/ tests/` ‚Äî must be clean before any commit.
- **Typing ceiling:** `python tools/typing_audit.py --dirs agentception/ tests/ --max-any 0`. Zero `Any` is the hard ceiling ‚Äî never raise it.
- **Tests:** Run individual files yourself; user runs full suite. Regression test for every bug fix: `test_<what_broke>_<fixed_behavior>`.
- **Show full output:** Never truncate, pipe through `head`/`tail`, or hide shell output.
- **After tests pass:** Update affected docs, then commit ‚Äî don't wait to be asked.

## Code standards

- **Every Python file** has `from __future__ import annotations` as the first import, immediately after the module docstring (if present). A module docstring may precede it ‚Äî nothing else may. No exceptions.
- Black formatting. Type hints everywhere ‚Äî 100% coverage, no untyped functions or parameters. `list[...]`/`dict[...]` style (never `List`, `Dict`, `Optional`).
- **Mypy before tests ‚Äî always.** Run `docker compose exec agentception mypy <path>` on every Python file you create or modify. Fix all type errors before running tests.
- Async for all I/O. `logging.getLogger(__name__)` ‚Äî never `print()`. `AC_*` env vars via `agentception/config.py`.
- Sparse logs with emoji prefixes (‚ùå error, ‚öÝÔ∏è warning, ‚úÖ success). No noise.
- Docstrings on public modules/classes/functions. "Why" over "what." Update docs in the same commit as code changes.

## Typing ‚Äî zero-tolerance rules

This codebase is operated by humans and agents. Strong types are the contract that lets both navigate it safely. There are no exceptions to these rules.

- **No `Any`. Ever.** `Any` destroys type safety for every caller downstream. If you think you need `Any`, you need a `TypedDict`, a `BaseModel`, a `Protocol`, or a more specific union. There is always a correct type ‚Äî find it.
- **No `object`. Ever.** `object` is `Any` with a different name for this purpose. If you know the shape, express it. If you don't, define it.
- **No naked collections.** `list`, `dict`, `set`, `tuple` with no type parameters are banned. Always write `list[str]`, `dict[str, int]`, `tuple[str, int, bool]`. A bare `list` tells agents and mypy nothing.
- **No `# type: ignore`.** If mypy flags something, fix the root cause ‚Äî don't silence it. A suppression comment is a lie baked into the source. If a third-party library forces the issue, use a typed stub or a narrow wrapper with a documented reason.
- **No casting or type coercion at call sites.** If you find yourself writing `cast(SomeType, value)` or forcing a type at a caller, the callee is returning the wrong type. Fix the callee. A cast at a call site means the type contract is broken upstream ‚Äî trace it to the source and fix it there.
- **Mypy strict = true, zero errors.** The mypy configuration in `pyproject.toml` runs with `strict = true`. All errors are real errors. Fixing them by weakening the config is not a fix.

### What to use instead

| Banned | Use instead |
|--------|-------------|
| `Any` | `TypedDict`, `BaseModel`, `Protocol`, a specific union type |
| `object` | The actual type or a constrained union |
| `list` (bare) | `list[X]` where X is the concrete element type |
| `dict` (bare) | `dict[K, V]` with concrete key and value types |
| `dict[str, X]` with known keys | `TypedDict` or `BaseModel` ‚Äî if you know the keys, name them |
| `cast(T, x)` | Fix the function that produces `x` to return `T` |
| `# type: ignore` | Fix the underlying type error |

### The known-keys rule

`list[X]` and `dict[K, V]` are fine when the collection *is* the abstraction ‚Äî a homogeneous sequence or a genuine dynamic lookup table where any key is valid. The key question: **do you know the keys at write time?**

- **Yes** ‚Üí use a `TypedDict` or `BaseModel`. A `dict[str, str]` whose keys are always `"title"`, `"body"`, and `"label"` is a `TypedDict` waiting to be written. Name it.
- **No** ‚Üí `dict[K, V]` is correct. A label-to-color map or a phase-to-count lookup has no fixed key structure; the parameterized dict is the right type.

`dict[str, Any]` or `dict[str, object]` with a known key structure is the highest-signal red flag in the codebase ‚Äî structured data being treated as unstructured. Always replace it with a named type.

## Testing

- **Four levels, all required:** unit tests, integration tests, regression tests (one per bug fix), and E2E tests where behavior crosses a service boundary. Omitting a level requires a documented reason in the PR.
- Naming: `test_<behavior>_<scenario>`. Shared fixtures in `tests/conftest.py`. `@pytest.mark.anyio` for async.
- **Agents own all broken tests ‚Äî not just theirs.** If you run the test suite and see a failing test, you are responsible for fixing it before merging your work. "This was broken before I got here" is not a valid reason to merge. Either fix it or open a blocking issue and get explicit sign-off. A PR that introduces or knowingly ignores a broken test will not be merged.
- Coverage: `docker compose exec agentception sh -c "export COVERAGE_FILE=/tmp/.coverage && python -m coverage run -m pytest tests/ -v && python -m coverage report --fail-under=80 --show-missing"`

## JS / CSS build discipline

The browser loads **compiled bundles**, not source files directly:

| Source | Bundle | Build command |
|--------|--------|---------------|
| `agentception/static/js/**/*.js` | `agentception/static/app.js` | `npm run build:js` |
| `agentception/static/scss/**/*.scss` | `agentception/static/app.css` | `npm run build:css` |
| both | both | `npm run build` |

**Rules:**
- After editing any `.js` file under `static/js/`, run `npm run build:js` before committing.
- After editing any `.scss` file under `static/scss/`, run `npm run build:css` before committing.
- When in doubt, run `npm run build` (does both).
- Never commit source changes to `static/js/` or `static/scss/` without a matching update to the bundle. A stale bundle is a silent runtime bug.

## Anti-patterns (never do these)

- **No legacy, no deprecated, no backwards compatibility.** Remove dead code, dead fields, dead endpoints on sight. Never add fallback paths for old API shapes.
- Business logic in route handlers. Global mutable state outside designated stores.
- Hardcoded model IDs, secrets, or URLs outside config.
- **`Any`, `object`, bare collections, `cast()`, or `# type: ignore`.** See the Typing section ‚Äî these are absolute bans, not guidelines.
- Tests on live APIs without skip guards. `sleep()` in tests. Asserting implementation details instead of behavior.
- **Merging with a known broken test.** If you see a failing test, own it. Fix it or block the PR. No exceptions.
- `print()` for diagnostics. Committing ephemeral scripts.
- Adding pip dependencies without updating `requirements.txt`. Running Python on the host.
- **Jinja2 `tojson` inside double-quoted HTML attributes.** `tojson` emits double-quoted JSON strings; wrapping them in a double-quoted attribute truncates the value at the first `"`. **Always use single-quoted HTML attributes when the value contains `tojson` output.** This applies to `x-data`, `x-text`, `:class`, `@click`, and any other Alpine.js or HTMX directive. Example ‚Äî correct: `x-data='fn({{ val | tojson }})'`; wrong: `x-data="fn({{ val | tojson }})"`. We introduced this bug three times before codifying this rule.

